00:01:19,795 --> 00:01:21,116
So with that, let's get started.

23
00:01:21,356 --> 00:01:22,456
So this was the spring of 2015.

24
00:01:22,957 --> 00:01:26,878
I had just left Insomniac to go indie, work on some of my own projects.

25
00:01:27,439 --> 00:01:29,860
And around that time, the Heart Machine team approached me.

26
00:01:30,260 --> 00:01:34,261
They were working on the indie action RPG Hyper Light Drifter and needed additional

27
00:01:34,322 --> 00:01:35,302
help with level design.

28
00:01:35,662 --> 00:01:38,103
So they came to me and they asked if I would be interested.

29
00:01:38,623 --> 00:01:40,024
And so I thought to myself, okay.

30
00:01:40,584 --> 00:01:45,491
All my level design knowledge and skills for action games thus far has been on big 3D games.

31
00:01:45,832 --> 00:01:48,115
I've done zero level design for 2D games.

32
00:01:48,636 --> 00:01:51,500
And I have no idea if any of my experience will apply at all.

33
00:01:51,920 --> 00:01:55,806
So I said, you know, yes, of course, I would love to do level design for you.

34
00:01:56,629 --> 00:02:00,651
So, they gave me their design test and I ran into a few struggles off the bat.

35
00:02:01,272 --> 00:02:07,115
These screenshots show the sort of 2D overhead but also from the side perspective of HyperLite

36
00:02:07,175 --> 00:02:10,337
and I started struggling with this when I was doing their test.

37
00:02:10,877 --> 00:02:16,220
In fact, I was so inexperienced in making 2D maps that I ended up mocking up structures

38
00:02:16,260 --> 00:02:21,043
in SketchUp and tilting the camera to help me figure out what that might look in this

39
00:02:21,103 --> 00:02:22,363
partial overhead view world.

40
00:02:23,464 --> 00:02:28,567
It worked out okay and once I got the hang of things, I was more easily able to lay things

41
00:02:28,687 --> 00:02:29,747
out for the test.

42
00:02:30,488 --> 00:02:33,410
And I ended up with a map that I thought was pretty okay and the team liked what I did

43
00:02:33,930 --> 00:02:35,191
so they brought me aboard.

44
00:02:35,811 --> 00:02:37,412
However, I was still worried a lot.

45
00:02:38,373 --> 00:02:40,575
about how a lot of my level design staples

46
00:02:41,075 --> 00:02:42,977
wouldn't translate from 3D.

47
00:02:43,437 --> 00:02:44,939
These were the sorts of design habits

48
00:02:45,119 --> 00:02:46,560
that by now were second nature to me,

49
00:02:46,821 --> 00:02:48,983
and I knew they wouldn't be applying in the same way.

50
00:02:49,864 --> 00:02:51,425
One fear, of course, was that I was very used

51
00:02:51,485 --> 00:02:53,427
to dealing with an outward facing camera

52
00:02:53,867 --> 00:02:55,449
and thinking about things in z-space,

53
00:02:55,649 --> 00:02:56,770
especially with things like.

54
00:02:57,491 --> 00:03:00,493
using distant landmarks to help player navigate through a large space,

55
00:03:00,974 --> 00:03:04,617
which of course landmarks don't work like that in an overhead game, so that wouldn't apply.

56
00:03:05,518 --> 00:03:10,803
Also, all of my experience setting up combat spaces was from this perspective of a forward-facing cone.

57
00:03:11,343 --> 00:03:16,408
So everything I knew about establishing front lines or mitigating player awareness about what they couldn't see

58
00:03:16,648 --> 00:03:19,270
wasn't necessarily going to be useful in this case.

59
00:03:20,471 --> 00:03:24,835
I also tended to rely a lot on verticality and spaces in 3D to make things interesting.

60
00:03:25,335 --> 00:03:27,157
But this was limited in the engine for Hyperlite.

61
00:03:27,177 --> 00:03:30,840
There was no way to make it possible to walk both under and over the same space.

62
00:03:31,460 --> 00:03:35,764
So a lot of the sneaky sort of wraparound things I had done in my design test wouldn't

63
00:03:35,784 --> 00:03:37,926
even be possible because of the engine constraints.

64
00:03:39,007 --> 00:03:40,467
So those were my big fears going in.

65
00:03:41,027 --> 00:03:43,428
But after I got started building some levels for the game,

66
00:03:43,608 --> 00:03:46,168
I realized there was still a lot of transferable skill

67
00:03:46,208 --> 00:03:47,669
going on from 3D to 2D.

68
00:03:48,269 --> 00:03:50,809
And ultimately, I ended up finding many, many parallels.

69
00:03:50,869 --> 00:03:51,850
But for the sake of this talk,

70
00:03:51,950 --> 00:03:54,370
I picked three big ones that I'm gonna talk about.

71
00:03:55,230 --> 00:03:56,731
So the first thing that carried over

72
00:03:56,871 --> 00:03:59,391
was my personal initial construction process.

73
00:03:59,571 --> 00:04:01,552
And what I mean by that is what I do

74
00:04:01,592 --> 00:04:03,752
when I start work on a brand new level from scratch

75
00:04:03,812 --> 00:04:05,553
with nothing but an empty scene before me.

76
00:04:06,693 --> 00:04:10,915
I'm mainly going to talk about my process of using established metrics as constraints

77
00:04:11,015 --> 00:04:12,996
for the very first parts of building a new level.

78
00:04:13,976 --> 00:04:18,438
So many designers I know when they're working on a new level, they sort of approach it like

79
00:04:18,458 --> 00:04:20,019
you would a subtractive sculpture.

80
00:04:20,039 --> 00:04:24,741
They block out big general shapes first and then go back over and shape those big blocks

81
00:04:24,781 --> 00:04:26,182
down into more detailed spaces.

82
00:04:26,622 --> 00:04:30,924
And I know a lot of level designers who work this way, but for whatever reason, I don't

83
00:04:31,004 --> 00:04:34,946
tend to use that approach beyond a very rough suggestion of what a layout might look at.

84
00:04:35,827 --> 00:04:40,712
And so my process is when starting a new level from scratch, I'll start laying out objects

85
00:04:40,912 --> 00:04:45,657
according to established distances that we've already figured out for the game and then

86
00:04:45,737 --> 00:04:49,020
growing the level outwards from those attached pieces.

87
00:04:49,741 --> 00:04:54,986
So then those shapes end up driving the bigger, more general shape of the whole level.

88
00:04:56,247 --> 00:05:00,910
And by metrics, I mean things like, you know, what's the minimum width of a corridor for

89
00:05:00,930 --> 00:05:02,550
an enemy to be able to navigate through it?

90
00:05:02,670 --> 00:05:06,532
Or what is the jump height and what is the jump distance and things like that.

91
00:05:06,632 --> 00:05:08,313
That's what I'm talking about when I say metrics.

92
00:05:09,477 --> 00:05:11,458
Here is an example from Sunset Overdrive.

93
00:05:11,558 --> 00:05:16,521
If you haven't played it, Sunset Overdrive is a very fast‑paced open‑world 3D shooter

94
00:05:17,002 --> 00:05:22,485
with a focus on traversal, so things like rail grinding, wall running, bouncing on things,

95
00:05:22,545 --> 00:05:22,905
et cetera.

96
00:05:23,786 --> 00:05:28,209
And this example is from a moment very early on in production where we had just decided

97
00:05:28,389 --> 00:05:31,831
that we were going to integrate combat with the player's move set.

98
00:05:31,991 --> 00:05:36,675
Before they were very separate and the combat was much more like a traditional 3D shooter.

99
00:05:37,515 --> 00:05:38,956
but we decided we were going to combine them.

100
00:05:39,396 --> 00:05:41,637
And all the designers were tasked with prototyping

101
00:05:41,677 --> 00:05:44,778
some spaces to figure out what that would feel like

102
00:05:44,798 --> 00:05:47,019
and what impact it would have on level design.

103
00:05:48,019 --> 00:05:51,180
So I ended up making this sort of food court prototype.

104
00:05:51,441 --> 00:05:53,441
It's very rough and focused on mechanics.

105
00:05:54,102 --> 00:05:55,762
And when I had sort of a rough idea,

106
00:05:55,782 --> 00:05:58,143
I wanted to do something with multiple heights

107
00:05:58,643 --> 00:06:00,904
that sort of spirals around some central feature.

108
00:06:01,665 --> 00:06:03,886
And specifically I was trying to make a space

109
00:06:03,966 --> 00:06:05,886
that would work in multiplayer.

110
00:06:06,527 --> 00:06:09,448
So let me walk you through my metrics as constraints process,

111
00:06:10,709 --> 00:06:12,330
what that looks like when I was building this.

112
00:06:12,850 --> 00:06:15,132
So I would start out with, say, a traversal piece,

113
00:06:15,192 --> 00:06:17,133
this bouncy awning the player can bounce on.

114
00:06:17,553 --> 00:06:20,215
And I'm thinking, OK, if the player bounced off of this,

115
00:06:20,275 --> 00:06:22,856
what's the range, like where they could land?

116
00:06:23,637 --> 00:06:26,561
And somewhere in this ring, so I'm going to put another bouncy object there.

117
00:06:27,022 --> 00:06:31,548
And I want a few options for the player, so I'll paste a couple of them, but I need to

118
00:06:31,568 --> 00:06:34,231
make sure they're at the right width so enemies can run through them.

119
00:06:34,732 --> 00:06:35,833
So now I have a couple more.

120
00:06:35,853 --> 00:06:36,294
Okay.

121
00:06:36,655 --> 00:06:39,498
You know, what's the next range of ‑‑

122
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,801
where the player can land.

123
00:06:43,261 --> 00:06:46,182
I want to put more stuff there, but I don't want things to be too flat.

124
00:06:46,242 --> 00:06:48,464
So let's elevate a little bit.

125
00:06:48,524 --> 00:06:51,145
What's the standard stair height?

126
00:06:51,545 --> 00:06:51,845
Okay.

127
00:06:51,865 --> 00:06:52,526
We'll put those in.

128
00:06:53,026 --> 00:06:56,608
You know, make sure there's more traversal options right in that area.

129
00:06:57,408 --> 00:07:02,251
And then again, I want to link this up with something else and here's the range and here's

130
00:07:02,691 --> 00:07:05,633
the width it has to be for enemies to navigate and so on and so forth.

131
00:07:06,133 --> 00:07:12,017
So it ended up sort of just like branching out paths from one traversal element to another.

132
00:07:12,998 --> 00:07:17,885
And as I mentioned, in this way, this construction method is a bit like a branching tree traversal

133
00:07:18,486 --> 00:07:23,674
in how small additions of connected spaces end up shaping the whole general space rather

134
00:07:23,714 --> 00:07:27,219
than the inverse method of starting with big general blocks and carving them down.

135
00:07:28,869 --> 00:07:32,972
So this metrics‑driven process for me ended up coming to play on HyperLite immediately

136
00:07:33,192 --> 00:07:37,535
with the first room the team had me build. So for context, they had been building out

137
00:07:37,575 --> 00:07:42,259
the east region, which is the water region in the game. They wanted something to contrast

138
00:07:42,299 --> 00:07:47,563
a lot of the tight, linear underground combat spaces they were making. So they said make

139
00:07:47,603 --> 00:07:53,087
a huge room that has multiple paths you can take through it and that features this particular

140
00:07:53,427 --> 00:07:53,848
new enemy.

141
00:07:54,929 --> 00:07:59,670
So I'm going to talk about this room called Mega Huge Lab, which you can see in its final

142
00:07:59,730 --> 00:08:00,290
form here.

143
00:08:00,911 --> 00:08:05,432
And for reference of how mega huge this room is, this rectangle here is the player's viewport.

144
00:08:05,532 --> 00:08:07,473
So this is how much they can see on screen at once.

145
00:08:08,133 --> 00:08:11,154
So it's quite big compared to a lot of rooms in the game.

146
00:08:11,754 --> 00:08:15,156
But before it made it to that state, it had humble beginnings here.

147
00:08:15,976 --> 00:08:18,277
Actually, technically it had even more humble beginnings.

148
00:08:18,417 --> 00:08:23,860
It was a super rough sketch to have a relative idea of some different connected spaces I want to do.

149
00:08:24,440 --> 00:08:29,122
But we're going to start here because this is where that carryover from my insomniac process started to come in.

150
00:08:29,202 --> 00:08:33,724
When I was faced with a blank room and had a vague idea of sort of what I wanted for the space.

151
00:08:34,304 --> 00:08:38,548
I found myself falling back on the same process that I did with that Sunset Overdrive prototype,

152
00:08:38,688 --> 00:08:43,733
which was start laying things out at distances that were already defined by existing metrics

153
00:08:43,773 --> 00:08:46,035
in the game and see how they connected.

154
00:08:46,836 --> 00:08:51,360
So in this case, the main metrics in question were the drifter's dash distance, like how

155
00:08:51,440 --> 00:08:53,902
far, like maximum, you could get across a gap.

156
00:08:54,743 --> 00:08:56,564
There were some fixed stair dimensions

157
00:08:56,604 --> 00:08:57,945
that had already been established

158
00:08:57,985 --> 00:09:00,407
that I used for distinguishing vertical layers.

159
00:09:00,927 --> 00:09:03,449
And then of course, just the viewport size for the player.

160
00:09:03,509 --> 00:09:06,672
That ended up being the most useful constraint

161
00:09:06,832 --> 00:09:07,412
when building.

162
00:09:08,413 --> 00:09:10,094
So similar to the Sunset prototype,

163
00:09:10,475 --> 00:09:14,298
I started out by laying out blocks of the viewport size

164
00:09:14,378 --> 00:09:17,600
to get an idea of how much would be on screen in each chunk.

165
00:09:17,981 --> 00:09:19,922
And it just sort of connected out

166
00:09:20,042 --> 00:09:21,083
as I was building it apart.

167
00:09:21,904 --> 00:09:25,308
And when laying out a section like this, which, you know, this is very early and went through

168
00:09:25,348 --> 00:09:31,016
many iterations later, but just to get something started to iterate on, you know, I would start

169
00:09:31,056 --> 00:09:35,682
with the drifter over here and measure what's his max dash distance here and here and just

170
00:09:35,862 --> 00:09:36,423
branch out.

171
00:09:37,917 --> 00:09:42,140
So if you're curious, this is what the evolution of that room looked like over time.

172
00:09:42,660 --> 00:09:48,483
It went through a number of iterations, driven by some enemy changes, a couple of hazard

173
00:09:48,523 --> 00:09:54,246
changes, but ultimately that rough initial connected structure, you know, still retained

174
00:09:54,446 --> 00:09:55,386
even in the final version.

175
00:09:56,903 --> 00:10:00,984
Alright, so even though that's a sort of specific thing to my personal work style, the basic

176
00:10:01,024 --> 00:10:06,246
steps and principles of how do I just initially get started constructing carried over quite

177
00:10:06,306 --> 00:10:09,266
well even though there were a lot of differences between 2D and 3D.

178
00:10:10,307 --> 00:10:15,208
So the second thing that carried over was this idea of using player defense and survival

179
00:10:15,288 --> 00:10:18,709
instincts to shape how I approach making the level.

180
00:10:19,389 --> 00:10:23,810
When I was at Insomniac, I worked under designer Drew Murray, and I remember him once saying

181
00:10:23,850 --> 00:10:24,510
this quote to me.

182
00:10:25,611 --> 00:10:30,054
Defensive capability of the player and shooters is more important to level design than offensive

183
00:10:30,094 --> 00:10:30,494
power.

184
00:10:31,094 --> 00:10:32,015
Which is very interesting.

185
00:10:32,035 --> 00:10:35,177
I had not considered that when I was a young fledgling designer.

186
00:10:35,558 --> 00:10:39,360
So in other words, how a player survives and how they feel about survival has a really

187
00:10:39,380 --> 00:10:41,642
big influence on how you build the level.

188
00:10:42,523 --> 00:10:44,844
Sometimes even more so than like enemy or weapon design.

189
00:10:45,425 --> 00:10:48,387
And this is things like, does your game have a health regen system?

190
00:10:48,427 --> 00:10:50,248
Do you have an explicit cover system?

191
00:10:50,808 --> 00:10:55,430
Basically, when the player is about to die, what mechanically do you expect them to do?

192
00:10:55,890 --> 00:10:58,550
And it has a huge effect on how you shape the space.

193
00:11:00,171 --> 00:11:04,612
So sunset overdrive was kind of weird because in this game, the more you were moving, the

194
00:11:04,672 --> 00:11:05,472
safer you were.

195
00:11:05,512 --> 00:11:10,553
You survived by traversing and going as fast as possible through all these chain traversals.

196
00:11:10,673 --> 00:11:14,574
And as a result, the level design doesn't have a lot of those traditional places of

197
00:11:14,634 --> 00:11:18,815
safety that the player might hide in that you might see in a more traditional third

198
00:11:18,835 --> 00:11:19,415
person shooter.

199
00:11:20,289 --> 00:11:21,971
But Resistance 3 and Hyper Light Drifter

200
00:11:22,051 --> 00:11:23,652
have more similar defensive models.

201
00:11:23,672 --> 00:11:24,954
So there's no regenerating health,

202
00:11:25,674 --> 00:11:27,416
and the things you have to do to replenish health

203
00:11:27,516 --> 00:11:29,918
tend to be pretty risky, be that run out

204
00:11:30,038 --> 00:11:32,080
and grab a pickup in a dangerous situation,

205
00:11:32,581 --> 00:11:35,644
or using those stocked health syringes in Hyper Light.

206
00:11:36,024 --> 00:11:37,566
And thematically, the world in both

207
00:11:37,826 --> 00:11:39,848
is meant to feel dangerous as a whole.

208
00:11:40,268 --> 00:11:42,150
So there were some elements of the level design

209
00:11:42,170 --> 00:11:44,052
that were similar as a result of that.

210
00:11:45,112 --> 00:11:48,895
So as a brief aside, a lot of the terminology I'm pulling from this section is from the

211
00:11:48,915 --> 00:11:52,698
book An Architectural Approach to Level Design by Christopher Totten, who I believe is in

212
00:11:52,738 --> 00:11:53,419
the room somewhere.

213
00:11:53,659 --> 00:11:55,541
There he is, right there in the middle.

214
00:11:56,321 --> 00:12:02,186
This book does a great job of generalizing a lot of level design principles so they apply

215
00:12:02,206 --> 00:12:03,227
across many genres.

216
00:12:03,527 --> 00:12:07,610
And there was a section in the book called Emotional Level Design Through Survival Instinct.

217
00:12:07,930 --> 00:12:11,632
And as I was reading it, I realized it was giving terminology to things that I'd been

218
00:12:11,672 --> 00:12:14,453
doing many years just from intuition or experience.

219
00:12:14,594 --> 00:12:16,595
So it was great to have those terms.

220
00:12:17,415 --> 00:12:20,636
One of these things is this idea of prospect and refuge space.

221
00:12:21,037 --> 00:12:26,319
So to quickly paraphrase, this boils down to prospect space is being vulnerable out

222
00:12:26,359 --> 00:12:28,920
in the open versus feeling safe in a hidey hole.

223
00:12:29,100 --> 00:12:31,101
And that's just the general gist of it.

224
00:12:31,802 --> 00:12:35,924
In a lot of situations in action games, you'll see these patterns where you'll have someone

225
00:12:35,944 --> 00:12:42,386
in a safe space have to go out in danger to get to a secondary refuge space further out.

226
00:12:42,406 --> 00:12:48,109
I really like this generalization because it's a principle that can apply broadly regardless

227
00:12:48,309 --> 00:12:50,870
of the camera, whether it's 3D or 2D.

228
00:12:51,290 --> 00:12:56,473
It's just a way of giving terminology to a natural habit of mine in level design.

229
00:12:57,273 --> 00:13:02,556
So like in Resistance 3, contrasting spaces of danger and safety were a frequent pattern.

230
00:13:02,896 --> 00:13:08,900
So you would often seek cover in these edge spaces that were concealed and often next

231
00:13:08,940 --> 00:13:15,263
to very open, tall ceiling spaces and this was a very common way of representing refuge

